SIMPLE: patch
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Patch
<hw>Patch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>pacche</ets>;
of uncertain origin, perh. for <ets>placche</ets>; cf. Prov. E.
<ets>platch</ets> patch, LG. <ets>plakk</ets>, <ets>plakke</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A piece of cloth, or other suitable material, sewed or
otherwise fixed upon a garment to repair or strengthen it, esp. upon an
old garment to cover a hole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Patches</qex> set upon a little breach.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A small piece of anything
used to repair a breach; <as>as, a <ex>patch</ex> on a kettle, a roof,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A small piece of black silk stuck on the face, or
neck, to hide a defect, or to heighten beauty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your black <qex>patches</qex> you wear variously.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <def>A piece of greased cloth or
leather used as wrapping for a rifle ball, to make it fit the
bore.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Fig.: Anything regarded as a patch; a small piece of
ground; a tract; a plot; <as>as, scattered <ex>patches</ex> of trees or
growing corn</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Employed about this <qex>patch</qex> of ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Bunyan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A block on the muzzle of a gun, to
do away with the effect of dispart, in sighting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A paltry fellow; a rogue; a ninny; a fool.</def>
<mark>[Obs. or Colloq.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Thou scurvy
<xex>patch</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Patch ice</b></col>, <cd>ice in overlapping pieces in the
sea.</cd> -- <col><b>Soft patch</b></col>, <cd>a patch for covering a
crack in a metallic vessel, as a steam boiler, consisting of soft
material, as putty, covered and held in place by a plate bolted or
riveted fast.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Patch
<hw>Patch</hw> <pr>(p⟦acr⟧ch)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Patched</conjf> <pr>(p⟦acr⟧cht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Patching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To mend
by sewing on a piece or pieces of cloth, leather, or the like; <as>as,
to <ex>patch</ex> a coat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mend with pieces; to repair with pieces festened
on; to repair clumsily; <as>as, to <ex>patch</ex> the roof of a
house</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To adorn, as the face, with a patch or
patches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ladies who <qex>patched</qex> both sides of their faces.</q>
<rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make of pieces or patches; to repair as with
patches; to arrange in a hasty or clumsy manner; -- generally with
<xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>patch</ex> up a truce</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧If you'll <xex>patch</xex> a quarrel.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>patchboard</ent>⟦br⟧
